<span style="margin-left: 0in;"><span class="AuthorDate"><span style="font-size: 12.0pt; text-decoration: none; text-underline: none;">Donnelly, 9</span></span>- staff writer for CQ weekly (John M. Donnelly, Nov. 23, 2009 “The Costs of Buying Time” http://library.cqpress.com.proxy.lib.umich.edu/cqweekly/document.php?id=weeklyreport111-000003253119&type=hitlist&num=0&) </span>

<span style="margin-left: 0in;">Even as President Obama contemplates how large a force of additional troops to send to Afghanistan, he reflected a growing concern last week that the war will deteriorate into a more protracted and bloody conflict. The president told reporters traveling with him on a weeklong tour of East Asia that he wants an “endgame” to the Afghanistan conflict so he won’t have to hand off the war to his successor. In doing so, Obama clearly indicated that he has his eye on a political clock that might run out in as few as three years. NOT ENOUGH TROOPS: As Marine patrols like the one above try to recapture Taliban-held areas, U.S. commanders are requesting as many as 40,000 more troops to carry out their mission. President Obama says he will give his answer soon. (Source: GETTY IMAGES / JOE RAEDLE.) <span class="BoldUnderline"><span style="text-decoration: none; text-underline: none;">On Capitol Hill, however, the Afghanistan clock is ticking much faster. With the war now in its ninth year, patience at home is wearing thin. And a growing chorus of lawmakers is now saying Obama has much less time before public support for the war — now below 50 percent — erodes to the point of collapse. The Democrats’ greatest fear is that the tipping point might occur just before the 2010 midterm elections — an awkward convergence of events that may imperil their jobs and jeopardize further congressional support for the war. So as Obama weighs a request</span></span> from Gen. Stanley A. McChrystal, his top commander in Afghanistan, <span class="BoldUnderline"><span style="text-decoration: none; text-underline: none;">for as many as 40,000 additional combat troops, lawmakers are focusing on their own political liabilities, which are the manifold costs of the conflict — in deaths, in dollars and in the deterioration of the military’s readiness to fight the next war. And they emphatically dismiss Obama’s multi-year time table, warning that whatever strategy he chooses must begin to show real progress by next fall at the latest. Otherwise, they warn, Democrats will abandon him. “He does not have that kind of time,” said Pennsylvania Democrat John P. Murtha,</span></span> chairman of the House Defense Appropriations Subcommittee, noting that many fellow Democrats rode into Congress on a wave of anti-war sentiment in the last two elections. “<span class="BoldUnderline"><span style="text-decoration: none; text-underline: none;">This will affect not only his election, this will affect our election.” Already, the number of soldiers who have been killed in Afghanistan is approaching the watershed 1,000 mark</span></span>, while thousands more have been horribly wounded and disfigured. <span class="BoldUnderline"><span style="text-decoration: none; text-underline: none;">Such casualty counts don’t include legions of servicemembers who suffer from debilitating psychological wounds that have resulted in catastrophic levels of anguish and suicide. With Obama expected to send over additional troops, all categories of casualties are certain to climb, further taxing public support for the war if the expected buildup doesn’t produce results quickly Lawmakers are also concerned about the financial cost of the Afghanistan fighting. Since U.S. troops invaded the country in late 2001, the war has cost U.S. taxpayers almost $227 billion. Congress is poised to provide almost $73 billion more for continuing operations this fiscal year. And for every 1,000 additional troops Obama sends to Afghanistan, the price will jump by $1 billion per year.</span></span> At a time when the nation’s economy is still fragile and unemployment remains high, <span class="BoldUnderline"><span style="text-decoration: none; text-underline: none;">big increases in defense spending are virtually guaranteed to spark debate over the president’s priorities. And then there is the cost of depleting the military’s readiness to fight in some other corner of the world, if called upon to do so. Almost a decade of fighting in Afghanistan and Iraq has worn down much of the military’s equipment and exhausted its ranks of experienced combat veterans</span></span>, and the military’s focus on counterinsurgency operations has left it ill-trained for conventional conflicts. <span class="BoldUnderline"><span style="text-decoration: none; text-underline: none;">Individually, each of these rising costs would generate major concern for lawmakers. Taken together, they confront Congress like a cluster of time bombs, all potentially set to explode in the fall of 2010, or certainly by 2012 if conditions in Afghanistan don’t improve by then</span></span>. The administration is also mindful of the looming political dangers of a war with too many costs. Last week, Secretary of State Hillary Rodham Clinton visited Kabul, where she urged President Hamid Karzai to strengthen his government’s accountability, a move that would give Congress greater confidence in U.S. military efforts there. Right now, the strongest support for the president’s plans for the war comes from Republicans, who have been urging Obama to approve McChrystal’s full troop request. War boosters argue that the 40,000 additional troops will tamp down the violence in Afghanistan and that the resulting stability will, in turn, shore up political support at home, just as George W. Bush’s 2007 surge of forces in Iraq eventually helped mollify critics of that conflict. An Increasingly Dangerous Place: Click Here to View Chart <span class="BoldUnderline"><span style="text-decoration: none; text-underline: none;">Many D</span><span style="text-decoration: none;">emocrats, however, fear the political consequences if a buildup of forces doesn’t produce results, at least before the sands in their political hourglass run out. Although most lawmakers have been supportive of the war in Afghanistan — launched with overwhelming approval by the public and Congress after the Sept. 11 terrorist attacks — they cannot ignore recent opinion surveys that for the first time show that half the country feels the war is no longer worth the cost.</span></span> Congress is unlikely to deny Obama the billions of dollars in appropriations for his troop buildup, which would probably be provided in a supplemental spending bill sometime next year. And experts say Congress </span>
<span style="margin-left: 0in;">may not deny future increases in spending either. Nonetheless, <span class="BoldUnderline"><span style="text-decoration: none; text-underline: none;">dampened voter enthusiasm suggests that an increasingly unpopular war would be difficult for the president to wage successfully without considerable political cost to himself and his party, experts say. “Many parts of the Democratic base will be sitting on their hands in the next election because they are so disenchanted,” said John Mueller, a political scientist at Ohio State University and an expert on public opinion in wartime</span></span>. Still, history shows that Americans can withstand substantial pain if they believe the military is winning a war, said Peter Feaver, a Duke University political scientist who worked on the National Security Council during the Clinton and Bush administrations. A corollary thought is that when Americans become dissatisfied with a war’s progress, either because of increasing violence or mounting casualties, public support erodes. In that light, <span class="BoldUnderline"><span style="text-decoration: none; text-underline: none;">Obama’s explanation of his new Afghanistan strategy and its benchmarks of progress will be as critical as his decision on additional forces, lawmakers say</span></span>. “A lot depends on the case that the president makes and the expectations that he sets when he announces his troop deployment decision,” said Susan Collins of Maine, a member the Senate Armed Services Committee and one of the few Republicans who is skeptical about adding forces in Afghanistan. “If he decides to follow Gen. McChrystal’s recommendation, or comes close to it, and presents to Congress and the American people a rationale, people will give him additional time — how long exactly, I don’t know,” she said. “I would think the public would want to see improvement by next year at this time, certainly.” The real drivers of public opinion, of course, will 